Scan a Page for Issues with Lighthouse & Axe Developer Tools

03
On this page
  1. Checking for Accessibility Issues with Lighthouse
  2. Scan for Issues with Axe Developer Tools

Checking for Accessibility Issues with Lighthouse

Lighthouse is a tool built into Chrome’s DevTools that generates scores for a page in a variety of areas, including Accessibility.

After checking for names and labels, alt attributes, and other common issues, Lighthouse has given us a score of 63 out of 100. This might be my lowest score ever!

It’s nice that Lighthouse points out that not every accessibility issue can be automatically detected as well as a suggested list of things to test manually, but it’s not my go-to tool.

If you are on a machine that is pretty locked down and won’t let you install third-party tools or browser extensions, Lighthouse could be a good alternative.

Scan for Issues with Axe Developer Tools

For general issue scanning, my go-to tool is Axe Developer Tools.

The Axe DevTools extension can be installed for Chrome, Firefox, and Edge. Some of the functionality is available for free, while other features require an account.

Clicking the “Scan ALL of my page” button will look for issues on the page.

An important thing to note is that Axe DevTools only scans what has been rendered on load. This means that it's possible that different issues could be found when our application is in different states.

If you scan the page again after expanding the MegaNav, you might find that Axe DevTools identifies additional issues.

Let’s look at the “Buttons must have discernible text” issue that Axe is reporting:

There are several Issue Tags present that point us to places we can go to learn more.

  • wcag2a is pointing us to WCAG 2.0 level A, which is included in WCAG 2.1.
  • wcag412 is pointing us to WCAG success criterion 4.1.2.
  • section508 and section508.22.a are related to US Government standards.
  • ACT is related to Automated Conformance Testing (ACT), a standard for writing automated accessibility testing rules.
  • cat.name-role-value is a category tag used internally by the axe-core API.

What we'll focus on for now is the WCAG related tag for guideline 4.1.2.

When checking WCAG Section 4.1.2 - Name, Role, Value we can see that this button issue is classified as “Level A”. This means it’s a must-do, which is backed up by the “critical” rating from Axe DevTools.

Luckily, Axe DevTools provides us with some guidance with options on how to solve these issues.
